Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist1:Thought: The core challenge in industrial weld inspection lies not only in detecting defects but also in ensuring that the input data is valid and inspectable—many images captured in real-world settings may be obstructed, poorly lit, or misaligned, rendering them unsuitable for defect detection. Most existing approaches assume that all incoming images are valid, leading to wasted computational resources and false alarms. Inspired by recent advances in domain adaptation and self-training frameworks (e.g., Papers 1–3), I propose a novel pre-classifier system that goes beyond simple anomaly detection by being *domain-aware* and *computationally adaptive*. Unlike traditional pre-filters that use fixed thresholds or basic autoencoders, this system actively learns what constitutes an "inspectable" image across varying operational domains (e.g., different welding types, camera setups, lighting conditions) without requiring labeled abnormal cases. It leverages contrastive learning to separate well-formed samples from corrupted ones, uses confidence-guided self-labeling to adapt to new environments, and dynamically adjusts its computational footprint based on image quality—processing high-confidence normal images with lightweight inference while allocating more resources to ambiguous cases. This creates a smart gateway that enhances both accuracy and efficiency in end-to-end quality control pipelines. The idea integrates principles from black-box adaptation (Paper 1), multi-view consistency (Paper 2), and discriminator-guided self-training (Paper 3), but applies them uniquely to the pre-classification of weld seam validity—an underexplored yet critical bottleneck.

