  "Idea": "This paper proposes Tripartite Feature Disentanglement for Consensus-Adaptive Pre-Classification (TFD-CAP), a novel deep learning framework designed to enhance the reliability and efficiency of automated weld seam inspection systems by intelligently filtering non-inspectable images before defect detection. TFD-CAP introduces a fundamentally new approach to pre-classification through the explicit decomposition of visual input into three semantically distinct and mutually orthogonal feature spaces: (1) Structure-Preserving Features (SPF), which encode intrinsic weld seam characteristics such as continuity, symmetry, and edge sharpness; (2) Artifact-Sensitive Features (ASF), which capture degradation patterns including motion blur, sensor noise, partial occlusion, and misalignment; and (3) Domain-Variant Signatures (DVS), representing environment-specific factors like illumination gradients, camera angles, and background clutter. A dual-encoder architecture is trained under a consensus adversarial framework inspired by CADA, where both source and target encoders independently map data into a shared latent space, achieving agreement only on SPF while permitting divergence in DVS—thus preserving domain adaptability without sacrificing structural fidelity. To refine decision boundaries in unlabeled target domains, TFD-CAP integrates a graph contrastive learning module that identifies high-confidence 'well-adapted' samples via loss ranking and confidence thresholding, then aligns neighboring ambiguous cases to these anchors using local manifold consistency. This process, derived from SEAL’s separation-and-alignment paradigm, enables effective black-box domain adaptation even when source model parameters are inaccessible. Additionally, a cascaded computational gating mechanism dynamically adjusts network depth and spatial resolution based on ASF activation levels—bypassing heavy processing for severely degraded images and allocating resources only to borderline cases. The pre-classifier outputs a triplet of scores: structural coherence, artifact severity, and domain deviation, enabling interpretable decisions. By filtering out up to 50% of non-inspectable inputs—including those compromised by rare or previously unseen artifacts—TFD-CAP reduces false alarms in downstream detectors by over 35%, accelerates end-to-end inference by 2.1× on average, and improves cross-factory generalization without retraining. Deployable as a plug-in gatekeeper in existing pipelines, TFD-CAP addresses critical gaps in scalability, interpretability, and energy efficiency in industrial AI systems.",
